                    <section class="content-section">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">The birth of low-code development</h2>
                        <p class="section-text">I had an opportunity to see the low-code market get established and evolve in the United States. I joined Outsystems just as they were expanding across North America. At that time, we were doing a lot of education about what low-code even was – explaining to potential customers that you could build applications without writing traditional code.</p>
                        <p class="section-text">The market was nascent, but the promise was clear: democratize application development and enable business users to build the tools they needed without relying solely on IT departments.</p>
                    </section>

                    <section class="content-section">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">The low-code market today</h2>
                        <p class="section-text">I saw the birth of this category, and now I've also seen it age. All enterprise software becomes bigger and more complex over time — it's a natural evolution. A desire to drive continued growth in a mature market leads vendors to add more features, more capabilities, and unfortunately, more complexity.</p>
                        <p class="section-text">What started as a simple promise to make application development accessible has, in many cases, evolved into platforms that require significant training and expertise to use effectively.</p>
                        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551288049-bebda4e38f71?w=600&h=300&fit=crop" alt="Low-code evolution" class="content-image">
                    </section>

                    <section class="content-section">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">The AI wild card</h2>
                        <p class="section-text">Generative AI is already a significant disruptor in the low-code space. I'm not convinced that everyone's going to want to build applications through pure text prompt-writing, but vendors are going to need to integrate AI capabilities thoughtfully to remain competitive.</p>
                        <p class="section-text">The key is finding the right balance between AI assistance and human control, between automation and customization. This is where the future of low-code development lies.</p>
                    </section>

                    <section class="content-section">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">Why Appsmith?</h2>
                        <p class="section-text">This will sound corny, but it's really about the people. At Appsmith, I saw thoughtful, forward-looking founders who are very open, willing to listen, and willing to engage. These are people that I respect and want to work with.</p>
                        <p class="section-text">Beyond the people, Appsmith represents what I believe low-code should be: developer-friendly, transparent, and truly empowering. It doesn't hide complexity behind black boxes but gives developers the control they need while still providing the speed benefits of low-code.</p>
                        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1522071820081-009f0129c71c?w=600&h=300&fit=crop" alt="Appsmith team collaboration" class="content-image">
                    </section>

                    <section class="content-section">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">What's next?</h2>
                        <p class="section-text">Like my time at Outsystems, we have a huge growth opportunity. Appsmith has a firm and growing presence in APAC and Europe, and we're starting to see some significant momentum in North America. For a company that's been primarily community-driven and open-source focused, there's tremendous potential to scale.</p>
                        <p class="section-text">The future is about making low-code development more accessible without sacrificing power or control. It's about meeting developers where they are and giving them the tools they need to build amazing applications quickly.</p>
                    </section>
